An Exploratory Data Analysis of the American Community Survey

Summary notes

This was the initial #TidyTuesday project, posted back on 30th April, 2018. Here is the motivating tweet from @thomas_mock

Welcome to #TidyTuesday week 5, let's explore the 2015 American Community Survey!

Data are 5 year average estimates at the county level from https://t.co/MB0WutGQLL via kaggle

Data: https://t.co/sElb4fcv3u
Source: https://t.co/4lhpdlcEcD#rstats #tidyverse #r4ds #dataviz pic.twitter.com/5zAtlMBiq0

— Tom Mock (@thomas_mock) April 30, 2018

We followed @thomas_mock‘s’ advice and plotted a selected set of graphs that would be useful in an exploratory data analysis (EDA).

Source data was taken from census.gov (via kaggle.com).

The data was tidy. The column titles were in PascalCase, so we transformed them to snake_case. A new multi-index was constructed from the unique identifiers, (state, county, census_id,). Any missing values were replaced with the column mean.

The data was further processed to find the percentage of the population that were women, and the income per captita ($000). The change to the income per capita was done to reduce its range, so all four selected variables shared approximately the same range. Given the size of the data, we selected a subset of the variables to explore. These were:

  • women (%age of population)
  • poverty
  • public work
  • income per cap ($000)

We sampled the data (n = 1250) to get around Altair’s max row limit for in-notebook DataFrames. A standardised view of the data was also created for the correlation and covariance heatmaps. (See the standardise function.)

Four visualisations were produced: The first shows a multiple boxplot; second is a matrix scatterplot; and third and fourth are heatmaps of the correlation and covariance matrices (of the standardised data.)

Dependencies

import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Constants

ACS_URL = ('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/'
           + 'master/data/2018/2018-04-30/week5_acs2015_county_data.csv')

Functions

def pascal_to_snake_case(s: str) -> str:
    return ''.join(['_' + c.lower() if c.isupper() else c for c in s])[1:]
def standardise(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """@pipeline.
    Standardise the dataframe.
    """
    df = df.transform(lambda x: (x - x.mean()) / x.std())
    return df

Main

Load the data

Load the raw data as a Pandas DataFrame 
acs = pd.read_csv(ACS_URL, encoding='latin-1')

Process the data

Rename columns and set a multi-level index 
v_acs = (
    acs
    .rename(columns={s: pascal_to_snake_case(s) for s in acs.columns})
    .set_index(['state', 'county', 'census_id'])
)
Get the proportion of popn that are female 
v_acs['prop_women'] = (
    v_acs['women']
    .div(v_acs[['men', 'women']].sum(axis=1))
    .mul(100)
    .round(3)
)
Get the income_per_cap in $000 
v_acs['income_per_cap_000'] = v_acs['income_per_cap'].div(1000)
Select and sample the data (n=1250) 
v_sample = (
    v_acs
    .get(['income_per_cap_000', 'prop_women', 'poverty', 'public_work'])
    .sample(n=1250, random_state=20180430)
)
Standardise the data 
v_zsample = v_sample.transform(standardise)
Get the correlation matrix 
corr_df = (
    v_zsample
    .corr()
    .reset_index(drop=False)
    .rename(columns={'index': 'X1'})
    .melt(id_vars='X1', var_name='X2', value_name='r')
    .round(2)
)
Get the covariance matrix 
cov_df = (
    v_zsample
    .cov()
    .reset_index(drop=False)
    .rename(columns={'index': 'X1'})
    .melt(id_vars='X1', var_name='X2', value_name='cov')
    .round(2)
)

Visualise the data

Plot multiple boxplots of the data 
alt.Chart(v_sample.melt()).mark_boxplot(size=50).encode(
    x='variable',
    y='value',
    color=alt.Color('variable', legend=None)
).properties(
    height=400,
    width=600,
    title='Multiple boxplots of the selected ACS data'
)
Plot a heatmap the correlation matrix 
base_r = alt.Chart(corr_df).encode(
    x='X1',
    y='X2'
)

heatmap = base_r.mark_rect().encode(
    color=alt.Color("r", scale=alt.Scale(scheme="turbo"))
).properties(
)

text = base_r.mark_text(baseline='middle', size=16).encode(
    text='r',
    color=alt.condition(
        abs(alt.datum.r) > 0.5,
        alt.value('white'),
        alt.value('black')
    )
)

(heatmap + text).properties(
    title='Correlation heatmap',
    width=400,
    height=400,
)
Plot a heatmap of the covariance matrix 
base_cov = alt.Chart(cov_df).encode(
    x='X1',
    y='X2'
)

heatmap = base_cov.mark_rect().encode(
    color=alt.Color("cov", scale=alt.Scale(scheme="turbo"))
)

text = base_cov.mark_text(baseline='middle', size=16).encode(
    text='cov',
    color=alt.condition(
        abs(alt.datum.cov) > 0.5,
        alt.value('white'),
        alt.value('black')
    )
)

(heatmap + text).properties(
    width=400,
    height=400,
    title='Covariance heatmap'
)
Plot a matrix scatterplot of the selected data 
g = sns.pairplot(
    v_sample,
    diag_kws={'bins': 20},
    height=1.8,
)
g.fig.suptitle('Matrix scatterplot of the selected ACS data', y= 1.04)
plt.show()
